#: ../../../guides/introducing_black_to_your_project.md:1
msgid "Introducing _Black_ to your project"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../guides/introducing_black_to_your_project.md:4
msgid ""
"This guide is incomplete. Contributions are welcomed and would be deeply "
"appreciated!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../guides/introducing_black_to_your_project.md:7
msgid "Avoiding ruining git blame"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../guides/introducing_black_to_your_project.md:9
msgid ""
"A long-standing argument against moving to automated code formatters like "
"_Black_ is that the migration will clutter up the output of `git blame`. "
"This was a valid argument, but since Git version 2.23, Git natively supports "
"[ignoring revisions in blame](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-"
"blame#Documentation/git-blame.txt---ignore-revltrevgt) with the `--ignore-"
"rev` option. You can also pass a file listing the revisions to ignore using "
"the `--ignore-revs-file` option. The changes made by the revision will be "
"ignored when assigning blame. Lines modified by an ignored revision will be "
"blamed on the previous revision that modified those lines."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../guides/introducing_black_to_your_project.md:18
msgid ""
"So when migrating your project's code style to _Black_, reformat everything "
"and commit the changes (preferably in one massive commit). Then put the full "
"40 characters commit identifier(s) into a file usually called `.git-blame-"
"ignore-revs` at the root of your project directory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../guides/introducing_black_to_your_project.md:23
msgid ""
"# Migrate code style to Black\n"
"5b4ab991dede475d393e9d69ec388fd6bd949699\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../guides/introducing_black_to_your_project.md:28
msgid ""
"Afterwards, you can pass that file to `git blame` and see clean and "
"meaningful blame information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../guides/introducing_black_to_your_project.md:31
msgid ""
"$ git blame important.py --ignore-revs-file .git-blame-ignore-revs\n"
"7a1ae265 (John Smith 2019-04-15 15:55:13 -0400 1) def "
"very_important_function(text, file):\n"
"abdfd8b0 (Alice Doe  2019-09-23 11:39:32 -0400 2)     text = text.lstrip()\n"
"7a1ae265 (John Smith 2019-04-15 15:55:13 -0400 3)     with open(file, \"r+"
"\") as f:\n"
"7a1ae265 (John Smith 2019-04-15 15:55:13 -0400 4)         f."
"write(formatted)\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../guides/introducing_black_to_your_project.md:39
msgid ""
"You can even configure `git` to automatically ignore revisions listed in a "
"file on every call to `git blame`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../guides/introducing_black_to_your_project.md:42
msgid "$ git config blame.ignoreRevsFile .git-blame-ignore-revs\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../guides/introducing_black_to_your_project.md:46
msgid ""
"**The one caveat is that some online Git-repositories do not yet support "
"ignoring revisions using their native blame UI.** So blame information will "
"be cluttered with a reformatting commit on those platforms. However, [GitHub]"
"(https://docs.github.com/en/repositories/working-with-files/using-files/"
"viewing-a-file#ignore-commits-in-the-blame-view) and [GitLab (since version "
"17.10)](https://about.gitlab.com/releases/2025/03/20/gitlab-17-10-released/"
"#ignore-specific-revisions-in-git-blame) both support `.git-blame-ignore-"
"revs` in blame views by default."
msgstr ""
